{{for|the horror comic published by Kitchen Sink Press|Death Rattle (comics)}}
'''Terminal respiratory secretions''' (or simply '''''terminal secretions'''''),<ref name=EMRPCC>{{cite web|title=Guidelines for the management of respiratory secretions in an imminently dying patient|url=http://www.emrpcc.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/RespsecretionsfinalDec2010.pdf|publisher=Eastern Metropolitan Region Palliative Care Consortium (Victoria)|accessdate=13 April 2014|author=Clinical Working Party|date=December 2010}},</ref> known colloquially as a '''death rattle''',<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cobbs|first1=Elizabeth L|title=When Death Is Near|url=http://www.msdmanuals.com/home/fundamentals/death-and-dying/when-death-is-near|website=MSD Manuals|publisher=MSD Manuals (Consumer Version) |accessdate=14 March 2016|display-authors=etal}}</ref> are sounds often produced by someone who is near death as a result of fluids such as [[saliva]] and [[Bronchus|bronchial]] secretions accumulating in the throat and upper chest.<ref name=EPERC>{{cite web|title=# 109 Death Rattle and Oral Secretions, 2nd ed|url=https://www.mypcnow.org/blank-wz9l3|website=Fast Facts|publisher=End-of-Life/Palliative Education Resource Center|accessdate=4 September 2017|author=Katherine Bickel|author2=Robert Arnold MD}}</ref> Those who are [[death|dying]] may lose their ability to [[swallowing|swallow]] and may have increased production of bronchial secretions, resulting in such an accumulation. Usually, two or three days earlier, the symptoms of approaching death can be observed as saliva accumulates in the throat, making it very difficult to take even a spoonful of water. Related symptoms can include [[Dyspnea|shortness of breath]] and rapid chest movement.  While death rattle is a strong indication that someone is near death,<ref>{{ cite journal | last1 = Wee | first1 = B. | last2 = Hillier | first2 = R. | editor1-last = Wee | editor1-first = B. | title = Interventions for noisy breathing in patients near to death | journal = Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews | issue = 1 | pages = CD005177 | year = 2008 | pmid = 18254072 | doi = 10.1002/14651858.CD005177.pub2 }}</ref> it can also be produced by other problems that cause interference with the swallowing reflex, such as [[Traumatic brain injury|brain injuries]].<ref name=EPERC/>

It is sometimes misinterpreted as the sound of the person [[choking]] to death, or alternatively, that they are [[gargling]]. 

== Timing ==
This symptom most commonly appears sometime during the last 24 hours of the person's life, although some people live somewhat longer.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/875629996|title=Oxford Textbook of Palliative Nursing|last=Ferrell|first=Betty|last2=Coyle|first2=Nessa|last3=Paice|first3=Judith A.|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=9780199332342|edition=4th|location=|pages=253–255|oclc=875629996}}</ref>

== Management ==
The dying person is usually unaware of the noisy breathing and is not disturbed by it, but some healthcare providers attempt to minimize the sound for the emotional comfort of family members and caregivers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.merckmanuals.com/home/fundamentals/death-and-dying/when-death-is-near|title=When Death Is Near - Fundamentals - Merck Manuals Consumer Version|work=Merck Manuals Consumer Version|access-date=2017-06-24|language=en-US}}</ref>  This may be done through repositioning the person, reducing the volume of [[IV fluids]] being given, or giving anticholinergic drugs to reduce secretions.<ref name=":0" /> In [[hospice]] and [[palliative care]], drugs such as [[glycopyrronium]], [[hyoscine hydrobromide]] ([[Hyoscine hydrobromide|scopolamine]]) or [[atropine]] may be used for their [[anticholinergic]] effects to reduce secretions and minimize this effect.<ref>{{cite journal|last2=Letizia|first2=M.|year=2009|title=Understanding and responding to the death rattle in dying patients|journal=Medsurg Nursing|volume=18|issue=1|pages=17–21, 32; quiz 22|pmid=19331295|last1=Hipp|first1=B.}}</ref>

